Jim started the '''Linux''' conference on Twics, Tokyo's first English-language Internet-connected watering hole, back in 1994.  Given another shared interest in eating, this quickly morphed into a lunch-and-Linux group known as the [http://tlug.jp/ Tokyo Linux Users Group].

Jim has a long history of playing with computers, from the Logo Lab at MIT in the 70s, to Heathkit and Atari in the 80s, to a design group for Chinon and later Creative Technology in the 90s.  He went to [http://maps.google.co.nz/maps?q=11+McKerrow+St,+Te+Anau&hl=en&ll=-45.413876,167.711792&spn=3.204536,4.768066&sll=-45.028892,166.950989&sspn=1.613121,2.384033&t=h&z=8 New Zealand] for ''a one year'' education software project that stretched to 7 years, but is now back in Tokyo.
